
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `avahi-resolve` baraye tabdil name-haye service Avahi be address IP estefade mishavad. Yani, komak mikonad ke address IP yek service ra az name-ash peyda konid, be jaye inke bekhahید khodetoon IP ra be yad dashte bashid. Avahi yek systeme, mesle Bonjour dar macOS, ke dastgah-ha mitoonan khodeshoon ro dar shabake moarefi konan.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `-n`  --> 📍 Faghat IP address ra chap mikonad, bedune chizi dige.
    🔹 `-p`  --> 🔑 Be jaye IP address, faghat hostname ra chap mikonad.
    🔹 `-v`  --> 🗣️ Eteela'ate bishtari dar morede chigozare chap mikonad (verbose mode).
    🔹 `--address` `NAME` --> 🎯 Name service ra ke mikhahid resolve konid moshakhas mikonad.
    🔹 `--service` `TYPE DOMAIN NAME` --> 📡 Name service, type va domain service ra ke mikhahid resolve konid moshakhas mikonad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ avahi-resolve --name mycomputer.local

    🔹 Address IP dastgah ba name "mycomputer.local" ra namayesh midahad.

    $ avahi-resolve --service _http._tcp local

    🔹 Tamame address-haye HTTP service ra dar domain "local" namayesh midahad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ avahi-resolve --name printer.local -n

    🔹 Faghat IP address printer ra chap mikonad, heech chize ezafi nist.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `avahi-resolve` command is used to resolve Avahi service names to IP addresses.  Essentially, it helps you find the IP address of a service by its name, instead of having to remember the IP directly. Avahi is a system, like Bonjour on macOS, that lets devices announce themselves on a network.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `-n`  --> 📍 Only print the IP address, nothing else.
    🔹 `-p`  --> 🔑 Print only the hostname, instead of the IP address.
    🔹 `-v`  --> 🗣️ Print more detailed information about the process (verbose mode).
    🔹 `--address` `NAME` --> 🎯 Specifies the service name to resolve.
    🔹 `--service` `TYPE DOMAIN NAME` --> 📡 Specifies the service name, type, and domain to resolve.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ avahi-resolve --name mycomputer.local

    🔹 Displays the IP address of the device named "mycomputer.local".

    $ avahi-resolve --service _http._tcp local

    🔹 Displays all HTTP service addresses in the "local" domain.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ avahi-resolve --name printer.local -n

    🔹 Only prints the IP address of the printer, nothing extra.
